What the compiler does:

    function foo(obj) {
        var a;                   // hoisted
        with (obj) {
            a = 2;               // take a from object if exists, otherwise take variable
        }
        console.log(&#39;foo, &#39;+ a);
    }


The first case creates an `a` variable in scope of the function, then the `var` statement is removed/hoisted and only the assignment part remains.

And while `obj` contains a property `a`, the value is assigned to the object&#39;s property with the `with` statement.

The local `a` did not recieved any value.

In the second call, there is no property of `a` and therefore the variable `a` gets a value.

